{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Generated function signature matches the interface (parameter names/types and return type) implied by the natural-language spec.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP is the failure boundary: correctness depends on how a real model interprets the spec and emits code. A mocked model can always return a perfect signature and hide real prompt-understanding failures. This is a single agentic step, so Workflow is not required.","test_description":"Run the service against a set of interface-sensitive prompts using the real LLM, parse/type-check the generated function signature, and assert exact match to expected parameter names/types/return type.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Generated implementation passes the provided tests on first or later attempt.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Pass/fail depends on real model code quality (LLM-DEP). Integration tests with canned outputs validate retry wiring but can miss true generation failures. Multi-step may occur, but minimum needed to catch real failure is still real model behavior.","test_description":"Use real LLM calls on representative prompts and the real local test harness; assert the service returns success within allowed attempts and that the final generated code passes the full suite.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.58,"Workflow":0.14}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"On failed tests, refinement prompt includes failure messages from the previous run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is primarily local handoff logic (test runner output -> prompt builder -> LLM request payload). MOCK-MISS applies if only testing prompt-builder in isolation; the bug often appears at module boundaries. Real model judgment is not required.","test_description":"Wire real orchestrator + test-result collector + prompt-construction modules with a stub LLM client that records input, force a test failure, then assert the next prompt contains the exact failure diagnostics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error containing all attempt artifacts/results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is retry-state orchestration and result aggregation across attempts. A pure unit test of a counter can miss cross-module state/serialization issues; real network/model behavior is unnecessary.","test_description":"Run orchestrator with deterministic failing generation/test components, execute full retry loop, and assert termination at exactly 3 attempts plus structured error payload with each attempt’s code and test results.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.63,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"End-to-end loop (generate -> test -> refine -> retest) succeeds on a task usually missed by a single LLM call.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP + LLM-DEP: correctness depends on sequential real agentic steps and feedback incorporation across calls. Single-call agentic tests cannot prove iterative recovery behavior.","test_description":"Use a benchmark prompt known to frequently fail on one-shot generation, run the full service with real LLM and real test execution, assert first attempt fails, refinement occurs, and a later attempt passes within 3 tries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.72}}]}
